03507nmm a2200613Ia 9780520341241DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20231990cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805203412417 a10.1525/97805203412412doi  a(DE-B1597)543148  a(OCoLC)1149449314  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPR1875.S45 L45 1990 7aLIT0060002bisacsh04a821/.11 aLeicester, H. Marshall, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Disenchanted Self :bRepresenting the Subject in the Canterbury Tales /cH. Marshall Leicester.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4cÂ©1990  a1 online resource (468 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe question of the "dramatic principle" in the Canterbury Tales, of whether and how the individual tales relate to the pilgrims who are supposed to tell them, has long been a central issue in the interpretation of Chaucer's work. Drawing on ideas from deconstruction, psychoanalysis, and social theory, Leicester proposes that Chaucer can lead us beyond the impasses of contemporary literary theory and suggests new approaches to questions of agency, representation, and the gendered imagination.Leicester reads the Canterbury Tales as radically voiced and redefines concepts like "self" and "character" in the light of current discussions of language and subjectivity. He argues for Chaucer's disenchanted practical understanding of the constructed character of the self, gender, and society, building his case through close readings of the Pardoner's, Wife of Bath's, and Knight's tales. His study is among the first major treatments of Chaucer's poetry utilizing the techniques of contemporary literary theory and provides new models for reading the poems while revising many older views of them and of Chaucer's relation to his age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian pilgrims and pilgrimages in literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aChristian pilgrims and pilgrimages in literature. 0aPersona (Literature). 0aPoetryxPsychological aspects. 0aPoetry. 0aPoint of view (Literature). 0aSelf in literature. 0aSelf-consciousness (Awareness) in literature. 0aSubjectivity in literature. 0aTales, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aTales, MedievalxPsychological aspects. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520341241?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520341241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520341241/original  aEBA_EMB  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles